Patch Set 1:

Hi Tony, I will comment here instead of in dallas-pipelines repo 😊

I tested your change again today, and it is stuck in the same task: [mirror-ocp-release : Fetch release signature]. Example here: https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/77000c96-8d6f-4247-b216-e50d25eeaa8b/jobStates#65abb7bc-c817-443f-ba2f-e4973e7b6d44:file51

I have been checking the tasks under roles/mirror-ocp-release/tasks/fetch.yml to check what could be happening, and I observed a difference between a passed job and this case.

In a passed job from the daily jobs, I could see that, in the task called [mirror-ocp-release : Check if signature.bin exists], exists = true, e.g. https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/3e5b4c38-04c8-469d-9f15-390b5b911e15/jobStates#bb6f0d0b-8928-4105-adea-5c4c86666c37:file44. So, as a result, the task [mirror-ocp-release : Fetch release signature] was skipped, due to that condition.

But, in our case, for OCP-4.10, that task results in exists = false, e.g. https://www.distributed-ci.io/jobs/77000c96-8d6f-4247-b216-e50d25eeaa8b/jobStates#65abb7bc-c817-443f-ba2f-e4973e7b6d44:file44. So, [mirror-ocp-release : Fetch release signature] was executed and failed.

Here, I have two comments:

-May it be due to the novelty of the OCP-4.10 version? Or because it is a nightly version? Because signature.bin file is missed, but it is present in other stable OCP releases.
-Apart from this, may it be a bug in [mirror-ocp-release : Fetch release signature] task? Because it should work, in case signature.bin is not present. Or is it, again, due to the novelty of OCP-4.10?

I hope it helps. I was trying to find a more clever solution because this mirror issue reminds me to CILAB-236, but it is not the same at all.

> -Apart from this, may it be a bug in [mirror-ocp-release : Fetch release signature] task? Because it should work, in case signature.bin is not present. Or is it, again, due to the novelty of OCP-4.10?
> 
> I hope it helps. I was trying to find a more clever solution because this mirror issue reminds me to CILAB-236, but it is not the same at all.

Thanks for taking a look in here. There's not much we can do at the moment, the issue is because there's no release signature yet for the latest nightly (https://mirror.openshift.com/pub/openshift-v4/clients/ocp-dev-preview/4.10.0-0.nightly-2021-09-23-210724/) it is strange, it's been a few hours and no signature yet.

I checked previous ones and the signatures are in there, there's a slight difference between the release and the signature, so it's possible to fail at time when we are running the job between those two actions. I think it's OK for nightly releases.


I'll wait a bit more for a new release or the signature before triggering another check.

Patch Set 4:

I continue the discussion with Tony, here some comments to keep track of the conversation:
I confirmed we can create a SR-IOV network without the target namespace, we can add it on the network template, it simply won't create the object NetworkAttachmentDefinition because the target namespace does not exists.
If we don't create the NS and do not make any reference of it in the Network template, we can still create the network but we'll have to update it later when adding the NS, so maybe easier to just reference it from the beginning even if we don't create the NS.
I didn't extend my testing to make sure a pod using SR-IOV with this approach will actually work, but we'll leave the CI to test that :)
We also confirmed the example-cnf NS is not created in the example-cnf-config repo, but we are going to add it and remove it from this CR to test, so stay tune for the next patch!

The change LGTM. Maybe it is worth to analyze a way of homogenize all this. What do you think?

A word about the plan.

Once it's deployed I'll work on the import. I already worked on this in the past but cancelled due to bugs, so I should be able to reuse this past work.

Then I'll ask some of you to have a look at the new system and UI so we can validate it's fine for the RDO community. We'll need people playing superadmin role which is useful to create new lists, fix problems, and act on RGPD requests; OSPO can help but additional people involved in the community would be better (current lists owners?).

Then we can schedule the migration. It will take longer than the www migration due to import time but the rest is similar: DNS switch and PR to redeploy with let's Encrypt support.
